<br>
You can also use DKP to your advantage, sick of people turning up late?  I used to award DKP something like:<br>
<br>
3pts Posted on forum would attend and arrived on time<br>
2pts Didn't post on forum, but arrived on time anyway<br>
1pt Attended Raid<br>
-2pts Posted on forum that they'd attend, and didn't.<br>
<br>
You can use DKP as a lever, aslong as the rules are known and visible to the membership (ie. no sending tells, &quot;i'll double your DKP if you come&quot;) then it's fair.<br>
<br>
DKP isn't a hard-line rules system, I laugh my head off when I read guilds that say &quot;we dont use dkp, we use a merit system&quot;.  So um, what exactly is DKP if not a measure of merit?<br>
<br>
The difference between DKP and 'merit' systems is that DKP rewards the same things that merit systems do, but merit systems keep on rewarding the same people whereas DKP spreads the loot evenly.<br>
<br>
I found it quite suprising that one of the top DKP scorers of my little band was a Necro I probably wouldn't have noticed on a merit system.  He kept his head down and never made a splash - but he was always there, supporting the guild and doing his bit - DKP rewarded him, merit would have overlooked him.<br>
<br>
Previous to that experience I was in a guild that adopted DKP during my time there, I was very much opposed to it at the inception - I considered DKP to be a way of the hard core of the guild keeping all the loot for themselves.  However DKP was introduced, and I actually liked it.<br>
<br>
I liked it because previously I had very much gone un-noticed but after it's introduction I was finaly getting rewarded for my efforts and earning the right to loot I didn't think that cleric05 would ever be allowed.<br>
<br>
Is it fair for cleric05 to get a decent item once in a while?  I ask you, what good is having a 5th cleric if they aren't geared?<br>
