<br>
* we use zero-sum DKP. The way it works is that if 3 items drop worth 10 points each and 30 people were there, everyone gets one point (10 * 3 / 30). That has a few important effects on things, first of all it keeps the system relatively balanced, in terms of an economy. If we priced every item at 100's of DKP, it wouldn't matter, because people would get lots of DKP when those expensive items dropped. It also incents us to do raids where there are lots of possible upgrades for people vs not so many. When we were doing ST key mobs, we had to add a bonus to things like Sontalak where the *only* reason to kill him was the key. We also had to add a bonus for people who showed up early to clear for Tunare. Other than those two things this system has worked well for us.<br>
<br>
* We allow people to buy stuff even if they're negative on DKP. Basically it's important that stuff doesn't rot, and we're not going to let an upgrade for someone rot simply because they don't have the DKP. However we do charge people full price for everything that's looted, which means some folks end up *very* negative. Rotting items do not get a reduction in price, otherwise people can just let it go to the rot tier and buy it on the cheap.<br>
<br>
Someone mentioned that a couple objections to DKP that I want to cover, at least to the degree that it works for our guild:<br>
<br>
1) DKP doesn't reward the people who take on more demanding roles in a raid.<br>
<br>
This is a frequent bias against DKP that shows up in merit guilds. However, ask yourself -- would Tank_23 like to tank the big mob too? How about Puller_4, think they want to pull some? Probably they do. Why can't they? Well, because their gear isn't as good. Oh, but the best gear is going to the MT and the puller, because they need it... If you're Tank_23 or Puller_4, you're sitting there going &quot;how do I ever get to tank then?&quot; And the answer is you don't, not unless someone doesn't show up, and when that happens you probably can't do as great a job simply because you've been getting the trickle-down loot.<br>
<br>
Merit systems are a self-reinforcing cycle when you distribute loot based on perceived need because of roles in a raid.<br>
<br>
<br>
2) DKP systems don't allow you to adjust quickly if you lose a key character<br>
<br>
If you're using a DKP system, loot is getting spread around to the people who raid the most. But the key is it's getting spread around. Ask on a class board and the most common factor separating DKP guilds from Merit guilds is that loot gets spread around. Merit guilds tend to have one strong MT, one strong puller, a few strong clerics, etc whereas DKP guilds tend to have several strong MT's, several strong pullers, and down the line. In a DKP guild, if you lose your MT, you have someone else with similar gear who can step in. You don't *have* to equip someone quickly, because you've been distributing the loot all along.<br>
<br>
In practice this works really well. If you look at NULL's top 4 tanks (in terms of gear), we all have very similar stats. Two of the tanks are on break right now, and we've been able to continue on without a hiccup, although of course we'd prefer they were around. The tanks who aren't as well equipped don't raid as much. If they raided more, they'd be right in the front lines too.<br>
<br>
We do allow for a few exceptions to the system. Agro weapons only go to warriors, for instance.<br>
<br>
A good percentage of our guild came from GC, where a merit system had been used. I personally did pretty well under the merit system, since as one of the guild's MT's I often got tank loot sent my way. It still frustrated me, though. There was often a strong bias to thinking like &quot;well, that has FT, it should go to a caster.&quot; Nevermind that the item in question was arguably the best range slot at that level for a tank as well. It also led to some really arbitrary decisions at time. One member didn't get an item they'd been dreaming about for years because the folks who decided merit had a brain fart that day. Instead it went to a relatively new member of the guild who'd never gotten anything with us before. I'm all for new members getting upgrades too, but that wouldn't have happened with a DKP system. <br>
<br>
The most important thing to know about merit systems, though, is that people bitch. I don't care how nice everyone is about it, they bitch about loot. And if you're an officer of a raiding guild, the last thing you want to hear is bitches about loot for the next 3 years. So either you get really draconian and kick people out for bitching, or you have major officer burnout. I'm sure that the raiding guilds who make merit work for them do it by having an extremely strong policy about loot whining. If you're not a raiding guild, the issue doesn't come up as much.<br>
<br>
In the end, I think it comes down to what kind of guild you are. Do you raid a lot? Do you have aspirations to raid more and bigger things? Are you a small guild and have to count on a few key people?<br>
<br>
If you're a small guild that doesn't raid much, it may be worth it to use merit simply to make sure your strongest players stay strong. Just keep in mind that you're going down that self-reinforcing rathole -- needing to keep rewarding someone because they have been rewarded in the past, and because you can't afford to have them leave.<br>
<br>
I'm obviously very pro DKP, so I'll mention some points where I think it doesn't work very well for us. First of all, we don't do many raids where there's only a small chance of a HUGE upgrade for someone dropping. It's basically not a good use of the guild's time. So I will probably never see a Crystallized Acid Bracer except via the Bazaar. We don't do NToV anymore, even though the Cloak of Thorns is an upgrade for many of our members, as are the gauntlets off Vyemm. Eashen isn't on our target list, despite the fact that his cloak, mask, and ring are an upgrade for many of us.<br>
<br>
Another place it's got some rough edges is that it's very easy for items to end up in &quot;odd&quot; places. One of our SK's won our first Improved Damage 4 neck off AD for instance. He loves the neck, it makes all his lifetaps bigger, and the stats are great. But it upset some people that an ID4 item would go to a hybrid tank before a caster (we lost one app over it). Personally I see this as the flipside to the merit problem, though. Either loot goes to very predictable places, or it can go to odd places sometimes. Which is better for your guild is up to you to decide.<br>
<br>
As an officer of a raiding guild, the thing that I appreciate most about DKP is that in the six months or so that we've been doing this, I've had to hear about a loot complaint exactly once. And I get to laugh when people tell me that SoAndSo has a reputation as a loot whore, since you're welcome to ask for everything you can use in our guild. Our biggest problem with loot is people NOT asking for things. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
