<br>
For larger guilds, some form of scoring, attendance logging is probably necessary, whether DKP based, or another points system, or even just counting loot and attendance and making sure that it's fairly evenly spread.<br>
<br>
One of the problems with merit is missing out on the quiet people - the ones that always turn up, do their job, but don't say much, don't get noticed. These are often the backbone of a guild, but can be missed out on loot because they're quiet.<br>
<br>
Conversely, merit can be used to equip people for the guild's goals, and to reward people for going above and beyond the call of duty.<br>
<br>
If it's a small 50-60 guild, which has a few tanks, they might want to equip their main tanks first, since the quality of gear of the MA has a large bearing on what mobs you can do. Merit can allow for that, but does leave the officers open to cries of favouritism.<br>
<br>
By &quot;above and beyond&quot;, I'm not necessarily referring to the puller dying 10 times in a raid - most people are prepared to die in raids. I'm talking about the people who spend hours running around tracking mobs to find raid targets, that sort of thing, when the rest of the guild are in exp groups asking the guild, &quot;When are we going to raid?&quot;<br>
